  "text": "Firefox initiates TLS connections through a layered architecture from HTTP to NSS:\n\n**Hop 1 - HTTP Connection Layer (netwerk/protocol/http/nsHttpConnection.cpp):**\nThe nsHttpConnection class manages HTTP connections. When HTTPS is required, the SetupSecondaryTLS() method (line ~1938) creates a new TLSTransportLayer instance to wrap the existing socket transport.\n\n**Hop 2 - TLS Transport Layer (netwerk/protocol/http/TLSTransportLayer.cpp):**\nTLSTransportLayer::Init() (line ~392) is the entry point for TLS establishment. It retrieves the 'ssl' socket provider from the nsSocketProviderService and calls provider->AddToSocket() to layer SSL/TLS on top of the raw socket.\n\n**Hop 3 - Socket Provider (security/manager/ssl/nsTLSSocketProvider.cpp):**\nnsTLSSocketProvider::AddToSocket() (line ~36) bridges the Necko networking layer to the NSS security layer. It delegates to nsSSLIOLayerAddToSocket() in nsNSSIOLayer, passing the file descriptor.\n\n**Hop 4 - NSS I/O Layer Integration (security/manager/ssl/nsNSSIOLayer.cpp & nsNSSIOLayer.h):**\nThe nsSSLIOLayerHelpers class (defined in nsNSSIOLayer.h, line ~38) bridges Necko to NSS. The nsSSLIOLayerAddToSocket() function (line ~1790) performs the critical handoff:\n- Creates an nsSSLIOLayerHelpers instance to manage TLS state\n- Calls nsSSLIOLayerImportFD() (line ~1269), which invokes SSL_ImportFD() from NSS\n- Registers I/O layer methods and callbacks for read/write operations\n- Sets up certificate validation and handshake callbacks\n\n**Hop 5 - NSS TLS Handshake (security/nss/lib/ssl/):**\nOnce the NSS socket layer is imported, TLS operations flow through NSPR's I/O methods:\n- **sslsecur.c**: Contains ssl_Do1stHandshake() (line ~33) which orchestrates the handshake state machine. It's called when read/write operations are attempted on the SSL socket.\n- **ssl3con.c**: Contains the SSL3/TLS protocol implementation. Functions like ssl3_SendClientHello(), ssl3_SendCertificate(), ssl3_SendFinished() execute the actual TLS message exchange.\n- The handshake is triggered implicitly during first read/write through NSPR's PRIOMethods layer (ssl3_HandleNewSessionTicket, ssl3_HandleServerHello, etc.)\n\nThe complete chain: Application → nsHttpConnection → TLSTransportLayer → nsTLSSocketProvider → nsNSSIOLayer (nsSSLIOLayerHelpers) → NSS (ssl_Do1stHandshake in sslsecur.c) → ssl3con.c (protocol implementation)"
}

